Applying BigGAN and DiffAugment: BigGAN + DiffAug¶

From cSAGAN, we continue add more complexity and introduce more components. This moves us into the direction of BigGAN and DiffAugment.

  • Orthogonal Regularization
  • Skip connections from Noise
  • Exponential Moving Average
  • DiffAugment
(Brock, Donahue and Simonyan, 2019)

Orthogonal Regularization. This enforces that the weights are orthogonal to each other, in other words tries to enforce that weights have their own specific purpose of doing different things and thus aren't redundant. (Brock, Donahue and Simonyan, 2019)

Skip Connections from Noise. Traditionally, the latent noise $z$ would only be connected to the first layer of the generator network. Instead, the concept of skip connections is introduced, connecting the noise $z$ to the entire convolution stack of the generator network. (Brock, Donahue and Simonyan, 2019)

Exponential moving average. Used in training GANs that helps to stabilize the training process. It works by maintaining a running average of the generator's parameters. Instead of updating the parameters directly, the EMA updates the parameters with a moving average of their past values, which perhaps can be thought of as similar to momentum in Batch Normalization (Yazc et al., 2019). As we see in the code implementation, we instead use the EMA generator parameters to calculate new samples instead of the current generator parameters. This is because using the generator with averaged parameters was found to actually improve the quality of the generated images over time and also helps in reducing the risk of mode collapse.

DiffAugment. Augments data during GAN training by applying image transformations to both real and generated images. Thus, this allows gradients to flow back to the generator, helping regularize the discriminator without changing the target distribution, and maintains a balance in the training process. The authors of DiffAugment use three specific types of transformations in their experiments: translation, CutOut, and color. (Zhao et al., 2020)

BigResNet Backbone
BigResNet in GANs, refers to a larger variant of ResNets. A BigResNet typically has more layers and more filters per layer than a standard ResNet, making it a more powerful and expressive architecture. The increased capacity of BigResNet allows it to generate higher resolution and more detailed images compared to a standard ResNet. As expected though, that using a BigResNet as the generator network in a GAN can be computationally expensive and require more memory, but the improved image quality can justify the additional computation cost.

Applying Data-to-Data Cross Entropy and Auxiliary Discriminative Classifier: ReACGAN + ADC + DiffAug¶

There are problems with the traditional Auxiliary Classifier GAN. When training ACGAN, a widely used type of cGAN with softmax cross-entropy loss as an auxiliary classifier, it usually struggles when the number of classes in the dataset increases. Additionally, it also has the problem of generating images with low diversity, to exploit the fact that specific images work best for both classifier and discriminator.

Data-to-Data Cross Entropy. This loss allows the discriminator visually compare the differences between multiple images and for data-to-data relationships to develop. This means information across multiple classes can also factor into the deciding factor, thus encouraging inter-class separability and intra-class diversity. (Kang et al., 2021)

Auxiliary Discriminative Classfiier (ADC) The typical ACGAN is generator agnostic, in that it is designed to work with any type of generator, and regardless of the architecture. This means there is no specific interaction with the generator, and thus the generator learns to produce label consistent results, leading to low intra class diversity. In essence, it produces strictly classifiable data. Thus, ADC fixes this by introducing the discriminator-like ability to the classifier, encouraging the generator to produce classifiable real datai nstead of classifiable fake data. (Kang et al., 2021)

Evaluation of Models ¶

We evaluate the models by performing 4 different analyses. They are:

  • Image Fidelity
  • Latent Space Evolution
  • Content Diversity
  • Semantic Consistency

Evaluating Image Fidelity¶

Here, we will use Inception Score and Frechet Inception Distance to analyze the metrics. The reason we use these two is because we want to see how our model stacks up to the best models in the world. As other metrics such as iFID and KID are difficult to find on the benchmarks as they are less popular, we avoid them, despite metrics such as KID proving to be a strong and robust metric. Both these metrics use a Pretrained Inception V3. Note that this model should be the InceptionV3 Tensorflow version and not the Pytorch, to perform accurate assessment.

Evaluating Content Diversity¶

Inception Score and Frechet Inception Distance (FID) aren't metrics that are intended to assess how diverse the content is (mode collapse). This is due to the fact that they both rely. Although FID does perform a comparison of fake distribution to real distribution, it is important to note that it compares the distribution of confidence labels, not necessarily the distribution of features themselves. This means that FID is good at catching Mode Dropping, but not Mode Collapse.

Thus, how can we assess this? One metric is to use Number of statistically-different bins (NDB Score). How does it work?

  1. Suppose we have a training set and a fake set.
  2. Using K-Means clustering, divide the training set into $K$ number of clusters
  3. Using the centroids of the K clusters, now allocate the images in the fake set to these $K$ clusters, thus forming $K$ bins.
  4. Conduct a two-sample test between the train and fake samples for each bin and calculate the Z-score.
  5. If the z-score is below a certain threshold, mark the bin as statistically different.
  6. Find the number of statistically different bins and divide by $K$.

Intuitively, one can think of it as each of the classes having 10 different bins. For example, a horse may have a white horse, a larger horse, small horse and so on. The fake set will then be assigned to the categorization it is most closest to. If any mode collapse happens where there is one feature that is prominent everywhere e.g. too many white horses for a given random distribution, then we know mode collapse is occuring.

In [68]:
ndb.plot_results()
In [69]:
ndb.print_results()

NSB results (K=100, data whitening):
BigGAN + DiffAug: NDB = 20, NDB/K = 0.200, JS = 0.0056
ReACGAN + ADC + DiffAug: NDB = 11, NDB/K = 0.110, JS = 0.0037
cSAGAN: NDB = 32, NDB/K = 0.320, JS = 0.0091
cSNGAN: NDB = 19, NDB/K = 0.190, JS = 0.0075

We observe:

  • ReACGAN has the lowest number of statistically different bins of 11
  • SAGAN has the highest number of statistically different bins of 32
  • BigGAN and cSNGAN are relatively the same at 20 and 19 respectively.
  • This tells us that although BigGAN has Image Fidelity performance levels very similar to ReACGAN, it suffers from some form of mode collapse where certain features of certain classes are missing.
  • Thus ReACGAN appears to be much more robust to this.

Evaluating Semantic Consistency¶

Here, we evaluate whether there may be perturbations across one dimension of latent space and also want to identify and observe the property of latent space disentanglement. How do we do this? I propose the idea of performing Linear Interpolation Analysis.

  1. To start off, we randomly sample our latent space from a Gaussian distribution.
  2. We then randomly select one dimension of the latent space to edit
  3. Next, we interpolate on this one dimension, from values -5 to 5. I chose these values as they would let us see the most extreme of both ends.
  4. Repeat with random selection of latent space dimensions.

NOTE that we want to reset -5 to 5 for every class, but ensure that everything else is the same. Even the originally sampled latent space itself.
Below, we have performed such on our best model ReACGAN.


There seems to be some entanglement here. Specifically, if we look at horse, both the color and size changes going along one dimension. However, this could be that the specific species of white horses are smaller, and so by making the horse more white, it also goes smaller as well.


We observe color interpolation along ReACGAN

Is there an alternative method? I have thought of perhaps running an exhausting search, for instance using the patch perception LPIPS and performing a pair-wise mean score, then finding the average. However, this was computationally intensive and difficult to implement.

A possible improvement to the current method I'm using, could be to attach some sort of feature extractor to the K Means clustering, so that we would be able to use the power of CNNs into choosing the embeddings instead of letting the pixel relationships develop themselves from the K Means algorithm (which would likely be more inaccurate than the proposed use of CNNs).

Conclusion¶

Thus, we decide that our final model should be ReACGAN + ADC + DiffAug as in summary it:

  1. Has the highest Inception Score and lowest Frechet Inception Distance
  2. Latent Space Evolution over time does not oscillate and seems to converge
  3. Suffers least from Mode collapse
  4. Obides by semantic consistency and latent space disentanglement
  5. Our final model also places around the 6th position on the paperswithcode leaderboard, in terms of Inception Score and 9th in terms of Frechet Inception Distance.

  • It was difficult trying to refer to and adapt modularized code into Jupyter Notebook, but am very happy that I was successful and managed to pull it off.

In the future:¶

I believe that exploring the use of more interesting evaluation metrics is something I am interested in looking more about. While assessing the fidelity of images is an important aspect of evaluating the performance of a generative model, it is also important to consider other metrics such as inter- and intra- class diversity, as well as disentanglement of the latent space. From my research, it appears that there is plenty of effort on assessing the fidelity of images, but there is still room for growth in terms of evaluating the diversity and disentanglement of the generated images. I hope to explore more of this domain in my own time; more robust and effective methods of evaluating these factors could provide a more comprehensive understanding of the capabilities of one's generative model.
